# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: headless-architecture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] A **content management system** (**CMS**) is a computer software used to manage the creation and modification of digital content (content management).
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] It is typically used for enterprise content management (ECM) and web content management (WCM).
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] ECM typically supports multiple users in a collaborative environment, by integrating document management, digital asset management, and record retention.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] Alternatively, WCM is the collaborative authoring for websites and may include text and embed graphics, photos, video, audio, maps, and program code that display content and interact with the user.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] There are two types of CMS installation: on-premises and cloud-based.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] On-premises installation means that the CMS software can be installed on the server.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] Notable CMSs which can be installed on-premises are Drupal, Grav, Joomla, ModX, Wordpress.org and others.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] The cloud-based CMS is hosted in the vendor's cloud environment.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] Publishing architectures vary significantly between systems.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] Traditional coupled CMSs tie the content repository to a single presentation layer, suiting organisations publishing to one channel.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] Headless CMSs separate the repository from presentation entirely, delivering content via APIs to websites, mobile applications, digital signage, or voice interfaces from a single source, an approach that has grown rapidly alongside the proliferation of digital touchpoints.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] Authoring environments typically enforce structured workflows in which content passes through defined review and approval stages before publication, with role-based permissions controlling what each user can create, edit, or publish.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] The core CMS features are: indexing, search and retrieval, format management, revision control, and management.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] Digital asset management systems are another type of CMS.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] They manage content with clearly defined author or ownership, such as documents, movies, pictures, phone numbers, and scientific data.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] Companies also use CMSs to store, control, revise, and publish documentation.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] There are also component content management systems (CCMS), which are CMSs that manage content at a modular level rather than as pages or articles.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] CCMSs are often used in technical communication, where many publications reuse the same content.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] Headless CMS, which separates content from its delivery layer, offers greater flexibility in content distribution across various platforms.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] According to W3Techs, the most widely used content management system is WordPress, used by 61.7% of websites as of March 2026.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] Other commonly used content management systems include Shopify, Wix, and Squarespace .
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] If the cross-reference mechanism is well designed, the reader will be able to follow each cross-reference to the referenced content whether the content is presented in print or electronically.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] An author working in a content management system is responsible for identifying subjects of interest that cross documents, and creating appropriate systems of cross-references to support readers who seek to understand those subjects.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] For an individual cross-reference, an author should ensure that location and content of the target of the cross-reference are clearly identified, and the reader can easily determine how to follow the cross-reference in each medium in which publication is supported.
[src:headless-architecture/content-management-system] Content strategy practitioners (known as content strategists) specialize in planning content to meet business needs, taking into account the processes for creating and maintaining the content, and the systems that support the content.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] The Fetch API provides a JavaScript interface for making HTTP requests and processing the responses.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] Fetch is the modern replacement for `XMLHttpRequest`: unlike `XMLHttpRequest`, which uses callbacks, Fetch is promise-based and is integrated with features of the modern web such as service workers and Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS).
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] With the Fetch API, you make a request by calling `fetch()`, which is available as a global function in both `window` and `worker` contexts.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] You pass it a `Request` object or a string containing the URL to fetch, along with an optional argument to configure the request.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` function returns a `Promise` which is fulfilled with a `Response` object representing the server's response.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] You can then check the request status and extract the body of the response in various formats, including text and JSON, by calling the appropriate method on the response.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] We declare a string containing the URL and then call `fetch()`, passing the URL with no extra options.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` function will reject the promise on some errors, but not if the server responds with an error status like `404`: so we also check the response status and throw if it is not OK.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] Otherwise, we fetch the response body content as JSON by calling the `json()` method of `Response`, and log one of its values.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that like `fetch()` itself, `json()` is asynchronous, as are all the other methods to access the response body content.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the rest of this page we'll look in more detail at the different stages of this process.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] 2. optionally, an object containing options to configure the request.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this section we'll look at some of the most commonly-used options.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] To read about all the options that can be given, see the `fetch()` reference page.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the `mode` option is set to `no-cors`, then `method` must be one of `GET`, `POST` or `HEAD`.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] The request body is the payload of the request: it's the thing the client is sending to the server.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] You cannot include a body with `GET` requests, but it's useful for requests that send content to the server, such as `POST` or `PUT` requests.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] For example, if you want to upload a file to the server, you might make a `POST` request and include the file as the request body.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] Other objects are converted to strings using their `toString()` method.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] See Locked and disturbed streams for more information.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] Request headers give the server information about the request: for example, in a `POST` request, the `Content-Type` header tells the server the format of the request's body.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] To set request headers, assign them to the `headers` option.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] Compared to using plain objects, the `Headers` object provides some additional input sanitization.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] For example, it normalizes header names to lowercase, strips leading and trailing whitespace from header values, and prevents certain headers from being set.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] Many headers are set automatically by the browser and can't be set by a script: these are called Forbidden request headers.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the `mode` option is set to `no-cors`, then the set of permitted headers is further restricted.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] `GET` requests don't have a body, but you can still send data to the server by appending it to the URL as a query string.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is a common way to send form data to the server.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] Whether a request can be made cross-origin or not is determined by the value of the `RequestInit.mode` option.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] This may take one of three values: `cors`, `same-origin`, or `no-cors`.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] See the reference documentation for `RequestInit.mode` for more details.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the context of the Fetch API, a credential is an extra piece of data sent along with the request that the server may use to authenticate the user.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] By default, credentials are only included in same-origin requests.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that if a cookie's `SameSite` attribute is set to `Strict` or `Lax`, then the cookie will not be sent cross-site, even if `credentials` is set to `include`.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] Including credentials in cross-origin requests can make a site vulnerable to CSRF attacks, so even if `credentials` is set to `include`, the server must also agree to their inclusion by including the `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` header in its response.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] Additionally, in this situation the server must explicitly specify the client's origin in the `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` response header (that is, `*` is not allowed).
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `Request()` constructor takes the same arguments as `fetch()` itself.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] This means that instead of passing options into `fetch()`, you can pass the same options to the `Request()` constructor, and then pass that object to `fetch()`.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] To make a request cancelable, create an `AbortController`, and assign its `AbortSignal` to the request's `signal` property.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] To cancel the request, call the controller's `abort()` method.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` call will reject the promise with an `AbortError` exception.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the request is aborted after the `fetch()` call has been fulfilled but before the response body has been read, then attempting to read the response body will reject with an `AbortError` exception.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] As soon as the browser has received the response status and headers from the server (and potentially before the response body itself has been received), the promise returned by `fetch()` is fulfilled with a `Response` object.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] The promise returned by `fetch()` will reject on some errors, such as a network error or a bad scheme.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] However, if the server responds with an error like `404`, then `fetch()` fulfills with a `Response`, so we have to check the status before we can read the response body.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `Response.status` property tells us the numerical status code, and the `Response.ok` property returns `true` if the status is in the 200 range.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] Just like the request, the response has a `headers` property which is a `Headers` object, and this contains any response headers that are exposed to scripts, subject to the exclusions made based on the response type.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] These are all asynchronous methods, returning a `Promise` which will be fulfilled with the body content.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] The method will throw an exception if the response body is not in the appropriate format: for example, if you call `json()` on a response that can't be parsed as JSON.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] Request and response bodies are actually `ReadableStream` objects, and whenever you read them, you're streaming the content.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is good for memory efficiency, because the browser doesn't have to buffer the entire response in memory before the caller retrieves it using a method like `json()`.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] This also means that the caller can process the content incrementally as it is received.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] If we use `Response.text()`, as above, we must wait until the whole file has been received before we can process any of it.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this example, we iterate asynchronously over the stream, processing each chunk as it arrives.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that when you access the body directly like this, you get the raw bytes of the response and must transform it yourself.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this case we call `ReadableStream.pipeThrough()` to pipe the response through a `TextDecoderStream`, which decodes the UTF-8-encoded body data as text.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the example below, we fetch a text resource and process it line by line, using a regular expression to look for line endings.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is a common pattern when implementing an offline cache with service workers.
[src:headless-architecture/fetch-api-using-fetch] The service worker wants to return the response to the app, but also to cache the response.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] Facebook started GraphQL development in 2012 and released a draft specification and reference implementation as open source in 2015.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] In 2018, GraphQL was moved to the newly established GraphQL Foundation, hosted by the non-profit Linux Foundation.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] On February 9, 2018, the GraphQL Schema Definition Language became part of the specification.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] Many popular public APIs adopted GraphQL as the default way to access them.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] These include public APIs of Facebook, GitHub, Yelp, Shopify, Google Directions API and many others.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] There is an annual GraphQL Conference featuring new developments of the protocol and organizations successfully using GraphQL.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] The event is hosted by the GraphQL Foundation with previous organizers incl.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] GraphQL supports reading, writing (mutating), and subscribing to changes to data (realtime updates – commonly implemented using WebSockets).
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] A GraphQL service is created by defining types with fields, then providing functions to resolve the data for each field.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] The types and fields make up what is known as the *schema definition*.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] The functions that retrieve and map the data are called *resolvers*.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] After being validated against the schema, a GraphQL query is executed by the server.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] The server returns a result that mirrors the shape of the original query, typically as JSON.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] With GraphQL, a business domain is modeled as a graph by defining a schema; within this schema, different types of nodes and their relations are defined.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] The GraphQL type system describes what data can be queried from the API.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] The collection of those capabilities is referred to as the service's *schema* and clients can use that schema to send queries to the API that return predictable results.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] The root type of a GraphQL schema, `Query` by default, contains all of the fields that can be queried.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] Other types define the objects and fields that the GraphQL server can return.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] There are several base types, called scalars, to represent things like strings, numbers, and IDs.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] Fields are defined as nullable by default, and a trailing exclamation mark can be used to make a field non-nullable (required).
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] A field can be defined as a list by wrapping the field's type in square brackets (for example, `authors: [String]`).
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] A GraphQL query defines the exact shape of the data needed by the client.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] Once validated and executed by the GraphQL server, the data is returned in the same shape.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] A GraphQL mutation allows for data to be created, updated, or deleted.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] Mutations generally contain *variables*, which allow data to be passed into the server from the client.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] The mutation also defines the shape of the data that will be returned to the client after the operation is complete.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] The variables are passed as an object with fields that match the variable names in the mutation.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] Once the operation is complete, the GraphQL server will return data matching the shape defined by the mutation.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] GraphQL also supports live updates sent from the server to client in an operation called a subscription.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] Again, the client defines the shape of the data that it needs whenever an update is made.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] When a mutation is made through the GraphQL server that updates the associated field, data is sent to all subscribed clients in the format setup through the subscription.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] While there's nothing that prevents a GraphQL service from being versioned just like any other API, GraphQL takes a strong opinion on avoiding versioning by providing the tools for the continuous evolution of a GraphQL schema.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] The `@deprecated` *built-in directive* is used within the type system definition language to indicate deprecated portions of a GraphQL service's schema, such as deprecated fields on a type or deprecated enum values.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] GraphQL only returns the data that's explicitly requested, so new capabilities can be added via new types or new fields on existing types without creating a breaking change.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] This has led to a common practice of always avoiding breaking changes and serving a versionless API.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] GraphQL does not provide a full-fledged graph query language such as SPARQL, or even in dialects of SQL that support transitive closure.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] For example, a GraphQL interface that reports the parents of an individual cannot return, in a single query, the set of all their ancestors.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] GraphQL APIs can be tested manually or with automated tools issuing GraphQL requests and verifying the correctness of the results.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] Automatic test generation is also possible.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] New requests may be produced through search-based techniques due to a typed schema and introspection capabilities.
[src:headless-architecture/graphql] Some of the software tools used for testing GraphQL implementations include Postman, Beeceptor, GraphiQL, Apollo Studio, GraphQL Hive, GraphQL Editor, and Step CI.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] A **headless content management system**, or **headless CMS**, is a back end-only web content management system that acts primarily as a content repository.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] A headless CMS makes content accessible via an API for display on any device, without a built-in front end or presentation layer.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] Cloud-first headless CMSes are those that were also built with a multi-tenant cloud model at their core and whose vendors promote software as a service (SaaS).
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] These vendors promise high availability, scalability, and full management of security, upgrades, and hotfixes on behalf of clients.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] Headless commerce uses the same setup to separate back-end product management and navigation from the front end of a website or other display types (e.g., IoT).
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] This is similar to how headless CMS's focus on creating content in the back end to be displayed on front ends via APIs.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] Headless CMS is similar to but distinct from the use of widgets or plugins on a site, like adding an online ordering and delivery plugin to a restaurant website.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] Most monolithic content management systems are "coupled", meaning that the content management application (CMA) and the content delivery application (CDA) come together in a single application.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] This makes back-end user tools, content editing and taxonomy, website design, and templates inseparable.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] A decoupled CMS and a headless CMS have a lot in common as a headless CMS is a *type* of decoupled architecture.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] The decoupled architecture allows for easier scalability and provides better security than coupled architecture, but it does not provide the same support for omnichannel delivery.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] There are multiple environments to manage, hiking up infrastructure and maintenance costs.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] The headless approach has also been applied to enterprise software outside of content management.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] Example of this include Salesforce, who introduced Headless 360 following their acquisition of Contentful, decoupling its CRM platform from its proprietary interface and making the underlying data accessible via API to external tools and AI.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] Headless CMS is a content management system (CMS) without a pre-built front-end presentation layer or templating system; instead, it provides a content repository and an API for managing the content.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] While this allows for greater flexibility and customizability, it can also present challenges or drawbacks for teams and organizations.
[src:headless-architecture/headless-content-management-system] The main downside is that it may require more effort to set up and configure and a certain level of web development knowledge on both the front and back end.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:headless-architecture/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:headless-architecture/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
